metadata.name: Abstract Calligraphy #91
metadata.description:
This work is inspired by Japanese avant-garde calligraphy (前衛書 Zenei-sho, or 墨象 Boku-shou). After World War II, the art of Japanese calligraphy was rapidly modernized. The ultimate result was avant-garde calligraphy that did not depict characters. They resembled the works of contemporary Western paintings of the same period, such as Abstract Expressionism and Art informel. In fact, some of the avant-garde calligraphy works were drawn with oil paint on canvas instead of Sumi ink on paper. So what is the difference between painting and calligraphy in those works?
A founder of avant-garde calligraphy said that the artistic essence of calligraphy art lies in the expression of a well-honed brushstroke, so the materials used are merely a medium. Then, is it possible for computer-drawn Bezier curves to become calligraphy art? This is an experiment in that.

This work is interactive. Clicking on the image or pressing the "m" key on the keyboard will randomly transform the shape of the strokes. There are 10 types of brushes. You can switch to other brushes by pressing the number keys on the keyboard (Touch devices switch with the direction of the swipe).
In addition, the strokes resize responsively to the window size, but the shape of the brush remains the same, so you can enjoy a different look by changing the screen's aspect ratio.

metadata.name: Uninhabitable #334
metadata.description:
Uninhabitable is a generative system built only from ellipses. The process of playing with different geometric and trigonometric disruptions gives rise to four different compositions which seek to evoque living constructions and environments. Besides the shape itself and its related distortion, the stroke weight of the lines plays a meaningful role in the piece. Following a discrete range [0.01,0.1,1] the weight reveals the process allowing the viewer to realize the trace of the huge amount of lines in each piece. This back and forth between scales and context is, while kind of stripping the code, part of my continuing interest on understanding the -usually- crazy paths of machines' way of thinking.

Press "h" to see it and high resolution and refresh to get back to the initial state. Press "h" to save it.

Uninhabitable is an original work by Iskra Velitchkova. 2021.

metadata.name: Pobbles #259
metadata.description:
The pobbles are generative blob-rocks: staring in silence, sometimes half-smiling, generally bored. 

• The pobbles are digital recreations of a series of rock-doodles by S.F.Kislev (my big brother). They are an attempt to capture a specific, singular handwriting, and evolve it using code. 
• See the original, 2014 handmade version here - https://pobbles.tez.page..
• Alternative titles considered include Peggles™, Plops™, Blobbies™, Floofs™, Flintstones™, Lardies™, Plumps™, Fats™ and Wet-Ones™. 
• The pobbles are written entirely in paper.js and p5.js. 
• The pobbles are an effort to take generative art into the realm of the cute. 
• They work well with toddlers.

🖨️ Collectors minting at the first auction tier receive a hand-crafted riso print of their pobble. Color variation between the file and the print will apply. 🖨️

metadata.name: A Bugged Forest #240
metadata.description:
A forest has stories to tell.
About times that were, about times that will be.
-
This project was minted in much unusual conditions. 
We gathered here, by 38 degrees heat. We belong to a crowd who loves stories, of civilisations at stake and deities, of afterlife and worship. We drank and hugged and chanted pagan hymns. We minted the Bugged Forest from our place on earth that we call Hell just for the fun of it. We are passionate, and loving, and angry and desperate. We, people of the soil, under a bugged sun.
-
This project is the long-form version of an algorithm that contains a bug. “The Bugged Tree”’s code was salvaged and stored and served as the core motivation and engine for an entire forest. Its concept is about releasing the control. I am a  byproduct of evolution, an iteration of that specie who wanted utter control, and which at some point, lost control over its own creation. As a generative artist, I chose to welcome the event of chance into my creative process. The symbolism in chance made me feel humble and free. Unwilling to make any change to a story that the Tree needed to tell me, as a listener, rather than a writer of my own idealised fantasies.
-
The iterations aren’t under control. They may be odd and off. We have to accept it. They are also plottable, press [s] in live mode to get a SVG. Attempt the plot at your own risk, as there’s a possibility for it to come near to impossibilities or cause paper or motor damage, and most certainly, a bugged drawing.
-
From Earth or from Hell, with love, yours truthfully, NFTBiker and zancan

metadata.name: Hand-Drawn Tree #21
metadata.description:
Inspired by sketches I'd draw in my college notebook during class. This piece generates tree drawings using a hand-drawn stroke style. If you look closely you'll see that the lines are made of thousands of tiny dots. Iterations vary by color scheme, background color, line thickness, density, and more, with a small chance of using a rainbow color palette.

Press R to re-run the drawing animation; enter to save the image in high quality. Enjoy!

metadata.name: Everyone needs more Liquidity #47
metadata.description:
Who doesn't?

This piece explores the dynamics of particle physics and liquid in an unbound system. In it, I set up a small space in which a particle system can play, bouncing off obstacles, creating rivers and falls, and responding to various physical constraints.

It is created using a webgl pipeline consisting of, primarily, a GPGPU particle system consisting of 16k particles in motion in real-time. The physics simulation is made possible using a compute shader (not really compute, given webgl, but you get the idea) which records the particles' position, velocity, age, and data to a texture for use by the point program. Each particle is rendered as a semi-transparent radial gradient, adding up to a distance field that is used to render the liquid.

metadata.name: 生成畫荷 #52
metadata.description:
It ain't hard to tell, code compiles, and then art reveals.

「天一生水，地六成之；地二生火，天七成之；天三生木，地八成之；地四生金，天九成之；天五生土，地十成之。天生地成，而行鬼神。」— 河圖

Heaven gens, earth erates, the acts of demons and gods, indefinitely, generate. 

荷花一現，河圖不見，生花成畫，心幸有憐。

I see that lotus, but this code does not render it. Flowers are generative, art is generative, and we feel. 

「自抒胸意，不襲前人；無人無我，無古無今」— 張大千七十七歲作

There is no I nor they, past or present. — Zhang Da Qian~1976

「墨落一時手不住，任譏老子做狂徒。」— 張大千八十四歲作

Oops! ink fell out of my hand. But, I, got it.  — Zhang Da Qian~1983

“We see things in things, 
then create and drop,
copyminters only look at commits, 
on github. 
Though they need not to peek,
my gen art’s free, to see, 
stuff on my mind, 
do not like, to be locked, in a file, 
it ain’t hard to smell.” — Zhang Da Qian x Nas x Jimi Wen

Press 1 to save png, only for Chrome, not Safari. Preview images are compressed.

License: CC BY-NC-ND 4.0
